03986nam a22005655i 9780822378365DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19921992ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223783657 a10.1515/97808223783652doi  a(DE-B1597)553833  a(OCoLC)1226680241  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aP119b.T78 1992 7aLAN0110002bisacsh04a414/.62221 aTsur, Reuven, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhat Makes Sound Patterns Expressive? :bThe Poetic Mode of Speech Perception /cReuven Tsur. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1992] 4c©1992  a1 online resource (188 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSound and Meaning: The Roman Jakobson Series in Linguistics and Poetics00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. How Do Sound Patterns Know They Are Expressive? The Poetic Mode of Speech Perception -- t2. On Musicality in Verse and Phonological Universals -- t3. Some Spatial and Tactile Metaphors for Sounds -- t4. A Reading of Rimbaud's "Voyelles" -- t5. Psychoanalytic or Cognitive Explanation -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPoets, academics, and those who simply speak a language are subject to mysterious intuitions about the perceptual qualities and emotional symbolism of the sounds of speech. Such intuitions are Reuven Tsur's point of departure in this investigation into the expressive effect of sound patterns, addressing questions of great concern for literary theorists and critics as well as for linguists and psychologists.Research in recent decades has established two distinct types of aural perception: a nonspeech mode, in which the acoustic signals are received in the manner of musical sounds or natural noises; and a speech mode, in which acoustic signals are excluded from awareness and only an abstract phonetic category is perceived. Here, Tsur proposes a third type of speech perception, a poetic mode in which some part of the acoustic signal becomes accessible, however faintly, to consciousness.Using Roman Jakobson's model of childhood acquisition of the phonological system, Tsur shows how the nonreferential babbling sounds made by infants form a basis for aesthetic valuation of language. He tests the intersubjective and intercultural validity of various spatial and tactile metaphors for certain sounds. Illustrating his insights with reference to particular literary texts, Tsur considers the relative merits of cognitive and psychoanalytic approaches to the emotional symbolism of speech sounds.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aSound symbolism. 0aSpeech perception. 0aVersification. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Phonetics & Phonology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822378365zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822378365423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822378365.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles